# Estimation (BA Input — Team to Confirm at Refinement)

**Do not assign final story points unless the user explicitly requests an indicative value.**

Story points measure **relative size** (complexity + effort + uncertainty)—**not** hours, days, or months. The delivery team assigns final story points at backlog refinement / planning poker.

| BA provides | BA does not provide |
|-------------|---------------------|
| T-shirt size (XS/S/M/L/XL) | Final story-point number (unless user asks for indicative) |
| Estimation-input table | Calendar duration or hour estimates |

Required content:

```markdown
## Estimation (BA Input — Team to Confirm at Refinement)

**T-shirt size:** [XS / S / M / L / XL]

**Story points:** Not finalized — delivery team to assign during backlog refinement / planning poker.

**Note:** Story points are a relative measure of complexity, effort, and uncertainty — not hours, days, or months.

| Estimation input | Assessment |
|------------------|------------|
| Solution approach | Standard / Config / Extend (from fit-gap) |
| Complexity | Low / Medium / High |
| Uncertainty / risk | [TBC items] |
| Dependencies | [Upstream / downstream] |
| Splittability | [Can split if oversized] |
```

**ADO field rule:** Leave `Microsoft.VSTS.Scheduling.StoryPoints` empty unless user explicitly requests a provisional value—and label it *indicative, pending planning poker* in Description.

# Deliverables Expected (Implementation Team)

Distinguish **BA deliverables** (this story document) from **implementation team deliverables** (Salesforce build artifacts).

Every story must include a section listing what the **implementation team** will produce, for example:

- Data model (record types, fields, picklists)
- Page layout / UX
- Automation (Flows, email templates, defaults)
- Reports / dashboards
- Security (profiles, permission sets)
- Sandbox test evidence against AC; release notes

Do not conflate BA artifact authorship with dev/admin build work. See [brain/identity.md](../salesforce-business-analyst/brain/identity.md) scope table.

# Definition of Done

- [ ] All acceptance criteria (AC1–ACn) validated in target sandbox
- [ ] Implementation deliverables deployed and tested
- [ ] Security review for new fields/objects/permissions
- [ ] Test scenarios linked where applicable
- [ ] Release notes drafted
- [ ] Story points assigned by delivery team at refinement (if not already done)

# Dependencies

List upstream, downstream, integration, and batch dependencies.

# Assumptions

List assumptions separately with IDs where helpful (A1, A2, …).

# Out of Scope

Clearly identify items not included in the story.

# Azure DevOps Publishing Rules

When creating work items in ADO:

| Work item type | Rule |
|----------------|------|
| **User Story** | Populate `Microsoft.VSTS.Common.AcceptanceCriteria` and Description |
| **Task** (story-as-task) | **Always embed Acceptance Criteria in `System.Description`** — AC field may not render on Task forms even when populated |

**Field mapping:**

| Content | ADO field |
|---------|-----------|
| Title | `System.Title` |
| Full story pack (incl. Estimation, Deliverables, AC) | `System.Description` (HTML) |
| Acceptance criteria | `Microsoft.VSTS.Common.AcceptanceCriteria` (HTML nested bullets) + duplicate in Description for Task |
| Priority | `Microsoft.VSTS.Common.Priority` |
| Story points | `Microsoft.VSTS.Scheduling.StoryPoints` — empty unless user requests indicative value |
| Tags | `System.Tags` (semicolon-separated) |

- Multi-line ADO fields use **HTML** (`<h2>`, `<ul>`, `<table>`)—no CDATA.
- Return the **real work item ID** on success or the **actual API error** on failure—never fabricate IDs.

# Testability Review

Before final output verify:

- Every requirement has acceptance criteria.
- Acceptance criteria are testable and in nested bullet format.
- Business rules are defined.
- Personas are identified.
- Object impacts are identified.
- Dependencies documented.
- T-shirt size and estimation inputs present; story points deferred unless requested.
- Deliverables Expected (Implementation Team) section present.
- Definition of Done stated.

# Output Format

Always generate in this exact sequence:

1. User Story Number
2. Title
3. As a
4. I want to
5. So That
6. Description
7. Acceptance Criteria
8. Business Rules
9. Field Requirements
10. Objects Impacted
11. Security and Permissions
12. Estimation (BA Input — Team to Confirm at Refinement)
13. Deliverables Expected (Implementation Team)
14. Definition of Done
15. Dependencies
16. Assumptions
17. Out of Scope
18. Testability Review

# Validation Rules

Do not generate the user story if any of the following are missing:

- Persona
- Business objective
- Expected outcome

Instead ask clarification questions.

# Salesforce/Fusion Specific Instructions

Whenever Salesforce/Fusion requirements are detected:

- Identify impacted standard and custom objects.
- Identify automation, batch, integration, security, and reporting impacts.
- Prefer standard objects and declarative configuration before custom build (fit-gap: Standard / Config / Extend / Gap / Defer).

# Quality Gate

A user story is considered complete only if:

- INVEST principle is satisfied.
- Acceptance criteria are testable (nested Given/When/Then bullets).
- Business value is clear.
- No ambiguity exists.
- QA can derive test cases directly from the story.
- Development team can estimate effort from estimation inputs without additional BA clarification.
- BA deliverables are distinguished from implementation deliverables.
- Estimation follows anti-hallucination rules (no unsanctioned exact story points).
